The student who has passed the course knows:
1) The principles of the clinical use of drugs used in dentistry (analgetics, antiallergic agents, local anesthetics, antiinflammatory agents, chemotherapeutics).
2) Poisonings caused by drugs, the principles of avoiding and treatment of poisonings. The concept and essence of polypharmacology.
3) The characteristics of pharmacotherapy in children, in elderly, in pregnant patients and in patients with diseases of different organs (diseases of the kidney, the respiratory organs, the liver and the heart).
4) Side-effects of drugs, allergy to drugs, the principles of avoiding and treatment of the side-effects.Objectives/eesmärkid:  1. To integrate basic pharmacological knowledge into the clinical practice 2. Practice to use databases, guidelines and medical reports 3. To analyse typical clinical situation and drug treatment. 4. To give overview of the main side effects and drug interactions.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  The student who has passed the course has a knowledge of the main principles of clinical pharmacology and evidence-based medicine and knows how to use these principles in practice, the student can also find, use and critically evaluate the information about drugs. The student can make desicions about the necessity of pharmacotherapy, can define a measureable treatment outcome and find the most effective and safest drug group and drug, to evaluate the suitability of the drug to the patient, to inform the patient about the treatment, to observe treatment and to evaluate its effectiveness.
The student who has passed the course is able to recognize the side-effects of the drugs and to treat them. The student knows drugs used in dentistry, their effects and side-effects.
